VIt was April, last year.
p4
aVI was on an evening out with friends
p5
aVto celebrate one of their birthdays.
p6
aVWe hadn't been all together for a couple of weeks;
p7
aVit was a perfect evening, as we were all reunited.
p8
aa(lp9
VAt the end of the evening,
p10
aVI caught the last underground train back to the other side of London.
p11
aVThe journey was smooth.
p12
aVI got back to my local station
p13
aVand I began the 10-minute walk home.
p14
aVAs I turned the corner onto my street,
p15
aVmy house in sight up ahead,
p16
aVI heard footsteps behind me
p17
aVthat seemed to have approached out of nowhere
p18
aVand were picking up pace.
p19
aVBefore I had time to process what was happening,
p20
aVa hand was clapped around my mouth so that I could not breathe,
p21
aVand the young man behind me dragged me to the ground,
p22
aVbeat my head repeatedly against the pavement
p23
aVuntil my face began to bleed,
p24
aVkicking me in the back and neck
p25
aVwhile he began to assault me,
p26
aVripping off my clothes and telling me to "shut up,"
p27
aVas I struggled to cry for help.
p28
aVWith each smack of my head to the concrete ground,
p29
aVa question echoed through my mind that still haunts me today:
p30
aV"Is this going to be how it all ends?"
p31
aa(lp32
VLittle could I have realized, I'd been followed the whole way
p33
aVfrom the moment I left the station.
p34
aVAnd hours later,
p35
aVI was standing topless and barelegged in front of the police,
p36
aVhaving the cuts and bruises on my naked body photographed
p37
aVfor forensic evidence.
p38
aa(lp39
VNow, there are few words to describe the all-consuming feelings
p40
aVof vulnerability, shame, upset and injustice that I was ridden with
p41
aVin that moment and for the weeks to come.
p42
aVBut wanting to find a way to condense these feelings
p43
aVinto something ordered that I could work through,
p44
aVI decided to do what felt most natural to me:
p45
aVI wrote about it.
p46
aa(lp47
VIt started out as a cathartic exercise.
p48
aVI wrote a letter to my assaulter,
p49
aVhumanizing him as "you,"
p50
aVto identify him as part of the very community
p51
aVthat he had so violently abused that night.
p52
aa(lp53
VStressing the tidal-wave effect of his actions,
p54
aVI wrote:
p55
aV"Did you ever think of the people in your life?
p56
aVI don't know who the people in your life are.
p57
aVI don't know anything about you.
p58
aVBut I do know this:
p59
aVyou did not just attack me that night.
p60
aVI'm a daughter, I'm a friend,
p61
aVI'm a sister, I'm a pupil,
p62
aVI'm a cousin, I'm a niece,
p63
aVI'm a neighbor;
p64
aVI'm the employee who served everyone coffee
p65
aVin the café under the railway.
p66
aVAnd all the people who form these relations to me
p67
aVmake up my community.
p68
aVAnd you assaulted every single one of them.
p69
aVYou violated the truth that I will never cease to fight for,
p70
aVand which all of these people represent:
p71
aVthat there are infinitely more good people in the world than bad."
p72
aa(lp73
VBut, determined not to let this one incident make me lose faith
p74
aVin the solidarity in my community or humanity as a whole,
p75
aVI recalled the 7/7 terrorist bombings in July 2005 on London transport,
p76
aVand how the mayor of London at the time, and indeed my own parents,
p77
aVhad insisted that we all get back on the tubes the next day,
p78
aVso we wouldn't be defined or changed
p79
aVby those that had made us feel unsafe.
p80
aa(lp81
VI told my attacker,
p82
aV"You've carried out your attack,
p83
aVbut now I'm getting back on my tube.
p84
aVMy community will not feel we are unsafe walking home after dark.
p85
aVWe will get on the last tubes home,
p86
aVand we will walk up our streets alone,
p87
aVbecause we will not ingrain or submit to the idea
p88
aVthat we are putting ourselves in danger in doing so.
p89
aVWe will continue to come together, like an army,
p90
aVwhen any member of our community is threatened.
p91
aVAnd this is a fight you will not win."
p92
aa(lp93
VAt the time of writing this letter \u2014
p94
